# Issue Analysis

The component renders twice because `doubled` is recalculated on every render as a **new array reference**, even when `items` hasn't changed. This breaks memoization and causes unnecessary re-renders if this component is wrapped in `React.memo()` or passed as a dependency elsewhere.

Additionally, if `items` is passed from a parent that recreates it on every render, the child will also re-render unnecessarily.

# Solution

Use `useMemo` to memoize the `doubled` calculation:

```jsx
function Counter({ items }) {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

  const doubled = useMemo(() => items.map(x => x * 2), [items]);

  return (
    <div onClick={() => setCount(c => c + 1)}>
      {count} ({doubled.join(',')})
    </div>
  );
}
```

## Why this works:
- `doubled` maintains the same reference as long as `items` doesn't change
- The dependency array `[items]` ensures recalculation only when `items` actually changes
- Prevents unnecessary renders if this component is memoized or if `doubled` is passed to child components

## Additional fix (if needed):

If `items` itself is being recreated on every parent render, also memoize it:

```jsx
function Counter({ items }) {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

  // Only if items comes from parent that recreates it
  const memoizedItems = useMemo(() => items, [items]);
  const doubled = useMemo(() => memoizedItems.map(x => x * 2), [memoizedItems]);

  return (
    <div onClick={() => setCount(c => c + 1)}>
      {count} ({doubled.join(',')})
    </div>
  );
}
```

Or wrap the parent component's item creation with `useMemo` as well.
